<article>
    <h1>What are the dif&#xAD;fer&#xAD;ent rat&#xAD;ings?</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201229/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-29"><time>2020-12-29</time></a>
        - <span>TECH</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A la­bel for the Level 1 rat­ing. There are four lev­els of rat­ing un­der the scheme.</p>
    <p>The Cy­ber­se­cu­rity La­belling Scheme has four lev­els of rat­ing, rep­re­sented by up to four as­terisks. The lev­els sig­nify the tiers of test­ing and assess­ment a prod­uct has un­der­gone, and the la­bels are valid for up to three years.</p>
    <p>For now, the cer­ti­fi­ca­tion scheme is open only to Wi-Fi routers and smart home hubs, but it will even­tu­ally be ex­panded to other kinds of tech­nol­ogy prod­ucts. Here is what get­ting each level of rat­ing en­tails:</p>
    <p>LEVEL 1</p>
    <p>The de­vel­oper has to com­plete and sub­mit a check­list, declar­ing that the prod­uct con­forms with se­cu­rity re­quire­ments such as en­sur­ing there is a unique de­fault pass­word, as well as pro­vi­sion of soft­ware up­dates.</p>
    <p>LEVEL 2</p>
    <p>The prod­uct has been de­vel­oped with se­cu­rity in­cor­po­rated into the de­sign. It is built with sup­port­ing pro­cesses in place to re­spond to com­mon threats.</p>
    <p>LEVEL 3</p>
    <p>The de­vel­oper must send the de­vice to a test­ing lab­o­ra­tory to re­view and as­sess its soft­ware. The de­vice’s soft­ware is checked for mal­ware, known vul­ner­a­bil­i­ties in third-party li­braries used, and soft­ware weak­nesses such as buf­fer overflow.</p>
    <p>LEVEL 4</p>
    <p>The de­vice must be tested by an ex­ter­nal lab, and have un­der­gone sim­u­lated cy­ber at­tacks to as­sess its se­cu­rity ca­pa­bil­i­ties.</p>
    <p>Cara Wong</p>

